{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640876"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:20:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:20:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17846"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17846"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.08,0.92,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10560"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77899"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10560"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17846"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63377"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"6970"},{"type":"tags","id":"8482"},{"type":"tags","id":"10139"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24621"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24625"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26717"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77899","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77899"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAfter feeding, insulin is released to help regulate blood glucose levels. This hormone is produced by beta cells located within the Islets of Langerhans, which release insulin into the circulation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organs contains the Islets of Langerhans?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gallbladder","Liver","Pancreas","Small intestine","Spleen"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreas\u003C/strong\u003E contains the Islets of Langerhans, which are clusters of cells that include beta cells responsible for producing and releasing insulin. Insulin is crucial for lowering blood glucose levels by facilitating the uptake of glucose into cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGallbladder\u003C/strong\u003E - The gall bladder stores bile, which aids in digestion, but does not produce insulin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver\u003C/strong\u003E - The liver plays a role in glucose metabolism but does not produce insulin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall intestine\u003C/strong\u003E - The small intestine is involved in nutrient absorption but does not produce insulin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpleen\u003C/strong\u003E - The spleen is involved in immune function and blood filtration, not insulin production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Beta cells within the Islets of Langerhans in the pancreas release insulin into the circulation.","Insulin is a hormone that helps regulate blood glucose levels after feeding."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040568. PMID: 33397651; PMCID: PMC7778149"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63377"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17